  <h2>What is half step down (E♭) tuning?</h2>
  <p>
    Every string drops one semitone: E♭–A♭–D♭–G♭–B♭–E♭. Chord shapes stay
    exactly the same as standard — everything just sounds a half step lower.
    Hendrix, Guns N' Roses, and Stevie Ray Vaughan lived here: it eases string
    tension, warms the tone, and sits better with many singers' range.
  </p>
  <h2>How to tune down a half step</h2>
  <p>
    Tap start, then work string by string from the thickest down. For each
    string the tuner highlights the right peg and tells you to loosen it
    slightly — a half step is a small turn, so go slowly. When the needle
    centers, the string gets a checkmark; six checkmarks and you're there.
  </p>
  <p>
    Playing with others in standard? Use the
